          "name": "Can I be charged with a DUI for driving after using cannabis?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, it is illegal to drive while impaired by any drug, including cannabis. Police have tools like the Standardized Field Sobriety Test (SFST) and drug recognition experts (DRE) to detect drug impairment."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the legal limits for THC while driving?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Canada has established legal limits for THC (the main psychoactive component of cannabis) in the blood. Driving with a THC level between 2 and 5 nanograms is a less serious offence, while driving with over 5 nanograms is a more serious DUI offence."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do police test for drug impairment?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "If police have a reasonable suspicion that a driver is impaired by a drug, they can demand a Standardized Field Sobriety Test. If the driver performs poorly, the officer can demand a blood, urine, or oral fluid sample."
          }
        }
